\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V(x)=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hamiltonian:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H=-\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2m}\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial x^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The spatial factor, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(x)$
\end_inset

, of the particular solution must satisfy the equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H\psi(x)=E\psi(x)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The eigenfunctions and eigenvalues are:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{align}\psi(x) & =\mathrm{e}^{\pm\imath kx}\\
E & =\frac{\hbar^{2}k^{2}}{2m}=\frac{p^{2}}{2m}
\end{align}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have defined 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\hbar k$
\end_inset

 based on the analogy to the classical expression for kinetic energy:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{\mathrm{cl}}=\frac{1}{2}mv_{\mathrm{cl}}^{2}=\frac{p_{\mathrm{cl}}^{2}}{2m}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the eigenvalues for a continuous spectrum, there is a physically
 acceptable solution for every value of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 (and every positive value of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Combining the spatial and temporal factors we obtain the particular solution:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{align}\Psi(x,t) & =\mathrm{e}^{\imath kx}\mathrm{e}^{-\imath Et/\hbar}\\
 & =\mathrm{e}^{\imath\left(kx-Et/\hbar\right)}\\
 & =\exp\left[\imath\left(kx-\frac{\hbar k^{2}}{2m}t\right)\right]
\end{align}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We discuss some of static features of $
\backslash
Psi(x,t)$ in the context of wave equations in general.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, we fix $t$ and vary $x$.
 Note that we will have the same value at $x_2$ and $x_1$ if $$ k(x_2 -
 x_1) = n2
\backslash
pi $$ Choosing $n = 1$ gives a unique definition of wavelength: $$ 
\backslash
lambda = x_2 - x_1 $$ and therefore $$ k
\backslash
lambda = 2
\backslash
pi $$ or $$ k = 
\backslash
frac{2
\backslash
pi}{
\backslash
lambda} $$
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, $k$ characterizes the the number of radians (which is $2
\backslash
pi$ times the number of cycles) per unit distance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
$k$ is called the _wavenumber_
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The definition of a wavenumber is a property of the solutions of any wave
 equation; what is unique to the Schroedinger equation is that $p = 
\backslash
hbar k = h/
\backslash
lambda$.
 This is the de Broglie relationship that preceded wave mechanics.
 Its physical significance is that the momentum proportional to the density
 of spatial oscillations, that is, number of oscillations per unit length.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
##
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now fix $x$ and vary $t$.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We note that any wave of the form $
\backslash
mathrm{e}^{
\backslash
imath 
\backslash
omega t}$ will have the same value at $t_2$ and $t_1$ if $$ 
\backslash
omega(t_2 - t_1) = n2
\backslash
pi $$
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Choosing $n = 1$ defines the fundamental period: $$ 
\backslash
tau = t_2 - t_1 $$ and thus $$ 
\backslash
omega 
\backslash
tau = 2
\backslash
pi $$
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
$
\backslash
omega$ characterizes the number of radians per unit time, and is called
 the _angular frequency_; it is a factor of $2
\backslash
pi$ larger than frequency $
\backslash
nu$, defined by: $$ 
\backslash
nu = 
\backslash
frac{1}{
\backslash
tau} $$
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Again, the definition of an angular frequency is a property of the solutions
 of any wave equation; what is unique to the Schroedinger equation is that
 $$ E = 
\backslash
hbar 
\backslash
omega = h 
\backslash
nu $$
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This relation is due to Einstein and also preceded wave mechanics by many
 years.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
##
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that for free particle: $$ 
\backslash
omega(k) = 
\backslash
frac{
\backslash
hbar k^2}{2m} $$ there is a simple functional relation between $
\backslash
omega$ and $k$.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This functional relationship is known as the _dispersion_ relation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As in other wave equations, the dispersion relation $
\backslash
omega(k)$ determines both the _phase velocity_ and _group velocity_ of the
 wave: $$ 
\backslash
begin{align} 
\backslash
text{phase velocity} & = 
\backslash
frac{
\backslash
omega}{k} 
\backslash

\backslash
 
\backslash
text{group velocity} & = 
\backslash
frac{
\backslash
partial
\backslash
omega}{
\backslash
partial k} 
\backslash
end{align} $$
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is the specific functional relationship between $
\backslash
omega$ and $k$ that distinguish between the motion of quantum waves from
 other waves that occur in nature.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
##
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Concept of phase velocity, rewrite the particular solution $$ 
\backslash
begin{align} 
\backslash
Psi(x,t) & = 
\backslash
exp
\backslash
left[ 
\backslash
imath 
\backslash
left( x - 
\backslash
frac{
\backslash
hbar k}{2m} t 
\backslash
right) 
\backslash
right] 
\backslash

\backslash
 & = 
\backslash
exp
\backslash
left[ 
\backslash
imath 
\backslash
left( x - v t 
\backslash
right) 
\backslash
right] 
\backslash
end{align} $$
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As long as the quantity $x - vt = 0$ we can change the values of $x$ and
 $t$ to obtain a constant value of the wave amplitude.
 This leads to the condition $x = vt$.
 Since $x$ increases as $t$ increases, $
\backslash
Psi(x,t)$ is a wave traveling to the right with a velocity $$ v = 
\backslash
frac{
\backslash
hbar k}{2m} = 
\backslash
frac{
\backslash
omega}{k} $$ called the _phase velocity_.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the momentum of the wavepacket, $p$, is equal to $
\backslash
hbar k$, the phase velocity is $p/2m$, which is one-half the classical expressio
n for the velocity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To obtain the classical behavior, we need to use a wavepacket and examine
 its _group velocity_.
\end_layout

