\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We see that for free particle the group velocity is independent of time,
 as in classical mechanics, and is completely determined by the distribution
 $a(k)$ at $t = 0$.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That the correspondence between classical and quantum mechanics in Eq.
 2.24 survives for an arbitrary distribution of $a(k)$ is surprising and
 represents a special case of Ehrenfest's theorem.
\end_layout

